\description{
Computes intraclass correlation coefficients for the numeric columns of a
matrix or data frame using the classical ANOVA mean-square formulas. The
output can be either a pairwise matrix across columns or an overall
all-column coefficient table.
}
\details{
Each column is treated as a measurement channel, method, or rater and each
row is treated as a subject.

The function supports two distinct analysis targets.
\itemize{
\item \code{scope = "pairwise"} answers: "how reliable is each specific column pair?"
Each estimate is based on exactly two columns and the output is a symmetric
matrix.
\item \code{scope = "overall"} answers: "how reliable is the full set of columns when
analysed jointly?" The output is the standard six-form overall ANOVA table
(\code{ICC1}, \code{ICC2}, \code{ICC3}, \code{ICC1k}, \code{ICC2k}, \code{ICC3k}).
}

These two scopes do not target the same quantity. The overall coefficients
are computed from the full multi-column ANOVA decomposition and are not
obtained by averaging or otherwise aggregating the pairwise matrix.

The three main choice arguments determine the classical ICC form.
\itemize{
\item \code{model} controls the rater structure:
\itemize{
\item \code{"oneway"} uses the one-way random-effects formulation.
\item \code{"twoway_random"} uses the two-way random-effects formulation.
\item \code{"twoway_mixed"} uses the two-way mixed-effects formulation.
}
\item \code{type} controls whether systematic column mean differences are penalized:
\itemize{
\item \code{"consistency"} targets consistency across columns.
\item \code{"agreement"} targets absolute agreement across columns.
}
\item \code{unit} controls whether reliability refers to one measurement or to the
average of multiple measurements:
\itemize{
\item \code{"single"} returns the single-measure coefficient.
\item \code{"average"} returns the average-measure coefficient.
}
}

The supported mappings are:
\itemize{
\item \verb{model = "oneway", type = "consistency", unit = "single"} gives \code{ICC1}.
\item \verb{model = "oneway", type = "consistency", unit = "average"} gives \code{ICC1k}.
\item \verb{model = "twoway_random", type = "agreement", unit = "single"} gives \code{ICC2}.
\item \verb{model = "twoway_random", type = "agreement", unit = "average"} gives \code{ICC2k}.
\item \verb{model = "twoway_random", type = "consistency", unit = "single"} gives \code{ICC3}.
\item \verb{model = "twoway_random", type = "consistency", unit = "average"} gives \code{ICC3k}.
\item \verb{model = "twoway_mixed", type = "agreement", unit = "single"} gives the
mixed-effects absolute-agreement analogue with the same classical point
formula as \code{ICC2}.
\item \verb{model = "twoway_mixed", type = "agreement", unit = "average"} gives the
corresponding average-measure analogue.
\item \verb{model = "twoway_mixed", type = "consistency", unit = "single"} gives \code{ICC3}.
\item \verb{model = "twoway_mixed", type = "consistency", unit = "average"} gives \code{ICC3k}.
}

The combination \verb{model = "oneway", type = "agreement"} is not defined here
and returns an error.

For \code{scope = "pairwise"}, the point estimates are computed in \verb{C++} directly
from the two-column ANOVA mean squares for each complete pair. For
\code{unit = "average"}, the implementation uses \code{k = 2} because each estimate is
based on exactly two columns.

For \code{scope = "overall"}, the point estimates are computed jointly from the
full wide matrix using the classical ANOVA decomposition over all columns.
Here the average-measure coefficients use \code{k = ncol(data)} after any row
filtering required by \code{na_method}.

Missing-data handling depends on \code{scope}:
\itemize{
\item with \code{na_method = "error"}, missing values are rejected before estimation;
\item with \code{na_method = "pairwise"} and \code{scope = "pairwise"}, each pair uses its
own complete-case overlap;
\item with \code{na_method = "pairwise"} and \code{scope = "overall"}, rows are restricted
to complete cases across all columns because the overall ANOVA requires a
common wide matrix.
}

When \code{ci = TRUE}, confidence intervals are obtained from the classical
F-based ANOVA formulas corresponding to the selected coefficient. For
\code{scope = "pairwise"}, non-estimable off-diagonal pairs return \code{NA}. For
\code{scope = "overall"}, the coefficient table includes interval columns for all
six standard rows.
}
\examples{
set.seed(123)
n <- 40
subj <- rnorm(n, sd = 1)
dat <- data.frame(
  m1 = subj + rnorm(n, sd = 0.3),
  m2 = 0.2 + subj + rnorm(n, sd = 0.4),
  m3 = -0.1 + subj + rnorm(n, sd = 0.5)
)

fit_icc <- icc(dat,
  model = "twoway_random",
  type = "agreement",
  unit = "single",
  scope = "pairwise"
)
print(fit_icc)
summary(fit_icc)

fit_icc_overall <- icc(dat, scope = "overall", ci = TRUE)
print(fit_icc_overall)
summary(fit_icc_overall)

}
